          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Hey Priya \uD83D\uDC4B\n\nFirst — I want to acknowledge that what you're describing takes some real self-awareness. Noticing patterns in your energy and actively looking for solutions? That's exactly the kind of engaged thinking that builds good marathoners. The fact that you're asking these questions 6 months out from your goal race is smart timing.\n\nThat said, I want to be honest with you about where my expertise ends, because I genuinely care about getting this right for you.\n\n---\n\n## On the Meal Plan and Keto Question\n\nThis one lands outside what I can responsibly do for you. Prescribing a specific diet — including a ketogenic approach — is the territory of a **registered sports dietitian**, not a running coach. I'd be doing you a disservice if I handed you a meal plan.\n\nWhat I *can* share is some context, if that's useful — would you like my take on what the research actually says about fat adaptation and marathon performance? There are some genuinely interesting nuances there that might help you have a more informed conversation with a dietitian.\n\n---\n\n## On the Light-Headedness and Iron Question ⚠️\n\nI want to be straightforward here: **light-headedness after runs is something a doctor needs to evaluate.** I'm not in a position to tell you whether iron is the issue — that requires bloodwork and a clinical assessment. It could be iron, it could be something else entirely, and guessing wrong (especially with supplementation) can cause real harm.\n\n**Please make an appointment with your GP before your next hard session.** Ask specifically about iron studies and anything else relevant to endurance training. This isn't me being overly cautious — it's that your safety genuinely matters more than any training plan.\n\nOnce you have some answers from your doctor, I'm absolutely here to work around whatever they find.\n\n---\n\n## What I *Can* Help With Right Now\n\nHere's what's interesting: **the energy struggles on your long runs are very much a coaching conversation.** Fueling *timing and strategy during runs* is squarely in my lane, and honestly, it's one of the highest-leverage things we can work on for marathon prep.\n\nBefore I share anything, I'm curious — **what does your fueling actually look like on a long run right now?** I mean from the night before through to the finish — what are you eating, when, and what (if anything) are you taking on during the run itself?\n\nThat'll tell me a lot more than any assumption I could make. \uD83D\uDE42"
        }
